!! Example 1 — minimal flat deck

Plain tagged slides; no grouping; arrows walk linearly.

```
<$button>
<$action-setfield $tiddler="$:/state/my-deck/open" text="yes"/>
Play deck
</$button>

<$reveal state="$:/state/my-deck/open" text="yes" type="match">
    <$present
        slides="[tag[Slides]sort[order]]"
        section-field="—"
        title="My deck"
        on-close-actions="<$action-setfield $tiddler='$:/state/my-deck/open' text=''/>"
    />
</$reveal>
```

Setting `section-field="—"` (a field nobody will have) makes every slide its own section — arrow keys then behave linearly, no vertical-stack confusion.

!! Example 2 — grouped deck

Each top-level section gets its own column of slides; vertical arrows walk within a section.

Author slides with fields:

* `tags: Slides`
* `section: intro` (or `body`, `wrap-up`, …)
* `caption: …`
* body text = wikitext

Then play with:

```
<$present
    slides="[tag[Slides]sort[order]]"
    section-field="section"
    caption-field="caption"
    title="Q2 review"
/>
```

!! Example 3 — playing a mindmap presentation

If you're using `rimir/mindmap` v0.3.0+, presentations are first-class. Set `mm.presentation` on a view tiddler, then click ''▶ Play'' in the preview-pane's Presentation tab (header bar or next to the modebar dropdown) — or press ''Shift+F2'' when focused in the canvas.

The page-template tiddler that handles the activation is `$:/plugins/rimir/mindmap/templates/present-overlay`. It reads the active presentation from `$:/state/rimir/mindmap/present-target` and wires the deck via the `mm-presentation-slides` filter operator.

!! Example 4 — authoring a custom layout

Add a tiddler `$:/plugins/rimir/present/layouts/bullets`:

```
\procedure render-bullets()
<div class="rr-present-layout my-bullets">
<h2>{{!!caption}}</h2>
<$list filter="[<currentTiddler>has[mm.slide-bullets]]" variable="_">
<ul>
<$list filter="[<currentTiddler>get[mm.slide-bullets]split[\n]!is[blank]]" variable="line">
<li><$wikify name="r" text=<<line>>><<r>></$wikify></li>
</$list>
</ul>
</$list>
</div>
\end render-bullets

<$transclude $variable="render-bullets"/>
```

Then on a slide tiddler set `mm.slide-layout=bullets` and put your bullet lines in `mm.slide-bullets` (one per line).

